# Production-Ready Code Quality (Guidance Only)

**Priority: complete the task.** Use these as guidance when they don’t block progress. Don’t get stuck on perfection.

## Structure & Organization

- Prefer one clear purpose per file/function/component when it’s easy to do.
- Use consistent naming (PascalCase components, camelCase for functions/variables) where you’re already touching that code.
- Remove obvious dead code (unused imports, commented blocks) only if it’s quick.

## Code Quality

- Prefer readable, obvious code over clever solutions.
- Add error handling when it’s straightforward; skip if it would delay finishing the task.
- Use types (TypeScript/JSDoc) when the project already has them; don’t refactor the whole codebase for types.
- Add dependencies only when needed; prefer small, well-maintained packages.

## Security & Environment

- Don’t commit API keys or secrets; use env vars and keep `.env` out of git.
- Validate/sanitize user input when you’re already working in that area.

## React (when editing React/JSX)

- Prefer functional components and hooks when writing new code.
- Use stable list keys (e.g. id) when you’re already rendering lists.
- Use semantic HTML and basic a11y when it doesn’t slow the task down.

## Finishing the Task

- Fix linter/type errors only if they would block run/build or the user asked for it; otherwise note them and move on.
- Match existing project style where practical; don’t rewrite working code for style alone.
- Prefer getting a working solution first; refine later if needed.
